{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658218"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:44:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:44:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20717"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97416"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13593"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11762"},{"type":"tags","id":"12520"},{"type":"tags","id":"12596"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32685"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97416"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how altered blood flow contributes to thrombosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laminar flow promotes contact between platelets and endothelium","Turbulence reduces endothelial activation","Altered flow prevents dilution of activated clotting factors","Turbulence primarily contributes to venous thrombosis","Stasis primarily contributes to arterial thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENormal blood flow maintains a laminar pattern where platelets are concentrated in the centre of the vessel, separated from the endothelium by a slower-moving plasma layer. This arrangement helps prevent inappropriate platelet adhesion and activation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDisruption of normal flow promotes thrombosis through several mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAltered flow prevents dilution of activated clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E - When blood flow is reduced (stasis), activated clotting factors and platelets accumulate rather than being washed away\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETurbulent flow causes endothelial damage and creates localised areas of stasis, particularly important in arterial thrombosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDisruption of laminar flow allows platelets to contact the vessel wall\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms proposed were:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaminar flow promotes contact between platelets and endothelium\u003C/strong\u003E - Laminar flow actually maintains separation between platelets and the vessel wall\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETurbulence reduces endothelial activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Turbulent flow damages and activates the endothelium\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETurbulence primarily contributes to venous thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Turbulence is more significant in arterial thrombosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStasis primarily contributes to arterial thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Stasis is predominantly associated with venous thrombosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis explains why venous thrombosis commonly occurs with immobility (stasis) while arterial thrombosis typically develops at sites of vessel irregularity where turbulence occurs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abnormal blood flow promotes thrombosis through stasis (accumulation of clotting factors) and turbulence (endothelial damage).","Venous thrombosis is primarily associated with stasis, while arterial thrombosis is primarily associated with turbulence.","Normal laminar flow keeps platelets in the centre of vessels, separated from the endothelium by a plasma layer."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; page 126."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T20:39:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T20:39:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13593"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97416"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11587"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haemodynamic disorders: thromboembolic disease and shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":3,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11762"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Bleeding and clotting","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"cre